banner.banner_desc: The banner of the Front Range Collective features a stark white mountain peak rising from a deep blue base, with three thick blue lines cutting diagonally downward from the peak like controlled waterways. A black circle encompassing the mountain suggests both unity and isolation, while angular dam-like patterns along the sides reinforce the region's water dominance. The flag's vertical orientation breaks from traditional horizontal formats, emphasizing the mountain-to-plains flow of power.
banner.description: As the climate warmed, the Front Range region was forced to build more and more dams to conserve their precious mountain runoff. After the collapse of the central U.S. government, the Collective seized control of the rivers flowing both east and west from the Rocky Mountains, gaining a stronghold on the water supply in the Desolate Frontiers. The culture of the region became increasingly fervent and insular, eventually restructuring into an eco-fascist commune that prioritized water use for the citizens of the Front Range over downriver areas in the deserts and plains.
banner.name: Front Range Collective

banner.banner_desc: The banner of the Front Range Collective features a stark white mountain peak rising from a deep blue base, with three thick blue lines cutting diagonally downward from the peak like controlled waterways. A black circle encompassing the mountain suggests both unity and isolation, while angular dam-like patterns along the sides reinforce the region's water dominance. The flag's vertical orientation breaks from traditional horizontal formats, emphasizing the mountain-to-plains flow of power.
banner.description: As the climate warmed, the Front Range region was forced to build more and more dams to conserve their precious mountain runoff. After the collapse of the central U.S. government, the Collective seized control of the rivers flowing both east and west from the Rocky Mountains, gaining a stronghold on the water supply in the Desolate Frontiers. The culture of the region became increasingly fervent and insular, eventually restructuring into an eco-fascist commune that prioritized water use for the citizens of the Front Range over downriver areas in the deserts and plains.
banner.name: Front Range Collective
